> Layers of flavour from warming pasanda spices, garlic, vegetables and coconut milk
> make this a comforting and nourishing soup that's perfect for autumn.
> Scoop up the lentils with the naan or dip it in your soup!

If you don't have a #toaster{}, heat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7 for
the naans.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1%unit}.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Cut the @tomato{1%medium} into 2cm chunks.

Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%carton} in a #sieve{}.

Zest and halve the @lime{1/2%unit}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Once hot, fry the
@diced British chicken breast{240%g}, onion and cook, stirring frequently, until
softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. IMPORTANT: Wash hands and utensils after handling raw
meat. Cook so there's no pink in the middle.

Add the @pasanda style seasoning{1%sachet}, lime zest and garlic. Stir-fry for
~{1%minute} more. Stir in the @coconut milk{180%ml}, lentils, @vegetable stock paste{15%g}
and @water{200%ml} until combined.

Bring the soup to the boil, then reduce the heat to low and simmer until slightly
thickened, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Once thickened, stir through the tomato chunks and @baby spinach{40%g} a handful
at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once the veg has been added to the soup, cut the @plain naans{2%unit} in half
widthways, then put in your toaster until golden.

If you're using the oven, put the naans onto a #baking tray{}. Sprinkle with a
little @water{} and pop them into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

When toasted, generously spread the @butter{10%g} over the naans.

Once the soup has thickened slightly, stir through the @mango chutney{40%g} and
a squeeze of lime juice.

Season to taste with @?salt{}, @?pepper{} and more lime juice if needed. Remove
from the heat.

Share the chicken and lentil soup between your bowls.

Serve with the buttery naans alongside.

Enjoy!